Understanding how floods in Emilia-Romagna shaped micro-level socio-political narratives

This notebook and slide deck showcase the key insights derived from the survey responses collected through the survey questionnaire prepared for this research. The survey questionnaire (Italian | English) is coded and distributed through Qualtrics platform. Survey responses are exported and downloaded to this repository to present key insights through data visualizations.

The survey aims to gather information on the attributes of the Narrative Policy Framework (NPF), including the Hero, Villain, Victim, and Moral of the Story. Traditionally, extracting these attributes relied on analyzing long-format textual data. However, previous approaches using open ended text-based questions often resulted in a high survey dropout rate.

To address this issue, the survey employs multiple-choice questions instead of open-ended text questions to infer these narrative components. By utilizing this approach, the survey aims to improve respondent engagement and completion rates.

The attributes identified through the NPF will later be compared and integrated with the attributes of macro-narratives of floods collected from newspaper articles in the subsequent stages of this research.

All the respondents are filtered based on their location. Only residents of Emilia-Romagna are allowed to continue the survey. More than 70 percentage of residents are living in Emilia-Romagna for more than 20 years.

30% of respondents are from Bologna. Approximately 10% of respondents are from each province of Modena, Ravenna, and Reggio Emilia. Following closely are Parma, Rimini, and Forl-Cesena, each representing around 8% of the respondents. Finally, around 7% of the respondents hail from Ferrara and Piacenza, respectively.

Questions related to May 2023 Floods of Emilia-Romagna

This section of the questionnaire contains questions about the floods in Emilia-Romagna that occurred in May 2023. These questions cover various aspects, including the perceived causes of the floods and whether exposure to an extreme weather event, in this case a floods, led to any behavioral changes in respondents.

Scroll down to see general questions related to May 2023 floods of Emilia-Romagna

What do you think was the main cause of the May 2023 floods? (For now we are only referring to the root cause.)

    Q9 Quale pensa sia stata la causa principale delle inondazioni del Maggio 2023? (Per ora ci riferiamo solo alla causa principale.)

    *	Piogge intense
    *	Gestione errata del bacino del fiume (per esempio deforestazione e costruzione edilizia di massa)
    *	Gestione errata del livello de fiume fiume (include il funzionamento delle paratoie per mantenere il livello dell'acqua)
    *	Cambiamento climatico
    *	Altro motivo (specificare)

According to respondents, the primary cause of the May 2023 floods in Emilia-Romagna was poor management of the river basin. This includes, but is not limited to, long-term planning activities such as deforestation and construction within the river basin. A closely ranked second cause, selected by 100 respondents, is heavy rain. Additionally, 91 respondents identified climate change as a primary cause of the flooding, while 68 respondents attributed the flooding to improper river management, including gate operations. Respondents were allowed to select only one option in this question.

What do you think is the main reason for vulnerability to floods?

    Q10 Quale pensa sia la ragione principale della vulnerabilit alle alluvioni?

    *	Infrastrutture urbane inadeguate per il drenaggio
    *	Pratiche Agricole che influiscono negativamente sul drenaggio dell'acqua
    *	Assenza di un piano di emergenza completo per le comunit locali.
    *	Sistemi di monitoraggio fluviale e di allerta insufficienti
    *	Altro (specificare)

More than 50 percent of respondents attribute the vulnerability of Emilia-Romagna to damages caused during floods to inadequate urban drainage infrastructure. Approximately 100 and 89 respondents, respectively, identify the absence of a comprehensive emergency plan for local communities and insufficient river monitoring and water level warning systems as contributing significantly to the vulnerability to damages during floods. Finally, 36 respondents attribute vulnerability to flood damages to poor agricultural practices.
